revision.text:
{{Use British English|date=March 2017}} {{Infobox journal | title = Annals of Philosophy | cover = | former_name = <!-- or |former_names= --> | abbreviation = Ann. Philos. | discipline = [[Natural philosophy]] | editor = Thomas Thomson | publisher = Robert Baldwin | country = United Kingdom | history = 1813-1827 | frequency = Monthly | openaccess = | license = | impact = | impact-year = | CODEN = | JSTOR = | LCCN = | OCLC = | website = | link1 = https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/2441#/summary | link1-name = Online archive | link2 = <!-- up to |link5= --> | link2-name = <!-- up to |link5-name= --> }} '''''Annals of Philosophy''''' was a [[learned journal]] founded in 1813 by the Scottish chemist [[Thomas Thomson (chemist)|Thomas Thomson]]. It shortly became a leader in its field of commercial scientific periodicals.{{sfn|Morrell|2004}} Contributors included <!--[[Friedrich Christian Accum]], -->[[John George Children]],{{sfn|Bettany|1887}} [[Edward Daniel Clarke]],{{sfn|Wroth|1887}} <!--[[William Daniel Conybeare]], -->[[Sir Philip Crampton, 1st Baronet|Philip Crampton]],{{sfn|Thomson|loc=Vol I, p 170}}{{sfn|Bettany|1888}} [[Alexander Crichton]],{{sfn|Boase|1888}} [[James Cumming (chemist)|James Cumming]],{{sfn|Bettany|1888a}} <!--[[Michael Faraday]], -->[[John Herapath]],{{sfn|Goodwin|1891}} [[William George Horner]],{{sfn|Thomson|loc=Vol VI, pp 281 – 283}} <!--[[Agnes Ibbetson]], -->[[Thomas Dick Lauder]],{{sfn|Henderson|1892}} [[John Miers (botanist)|John Miers]],{{sfn|Boulger|1894}} [[Matthew Paul Moyle]],{{sfn|Boase|1894}} [[Robert Porrett]],{{sfn|Hartog|1896}} [[James Thomson (minister)|James Thomson]],{{sfn|Carlyle|1898}} and [[Charles Wheatstone]].{{sfn|Thompson|1899}}
Thomson edited it until 1821, when he was succeeded in 1821 by [[Richard Phillips (chemist)|Richard Phillips]]. The journal was bought by [[Richard Taylor (editor)|Richard Taylor]] in 1827, and closed down for the benefit of the ''[[Philosophical Magazine]]''.{{sfn|Harden|1898}}
The ''Annals of Philosophy'' were issued monthly following a standard pattern. Often the first article was a biographical article (10 pages) on a living or recently deceased scientist. This was then followed by a series of extended pieces (5-10 pages) on particular topics, sometimes by eminent authors. Then there were shorter news items and correspondence. Summaries followed: first of the proceedings of learned bodies (Royal Society, Linnean, French Institute -if available: the [[Napoleonic Wars]] made communications with the continent difficult at first,{{sfn|Thomson|loc=Vol III, pp iii – iv}} etc.), then of patents, and finally of new books. The last section was a [[meteorological]] journal. Every six months a title page, index, and preface were issued which could be bound before the six monthly issues to make a half-yearly volume.{{sfn|Thomson|loc=Vol I, p iii}} Including front matter, volumes were just under 500 pages each.{{sfn|Thomson|loc=Vol I, pp v–viii}}{{sfn|Thomson|loc=Vol II, pp iv – viii}}{{sfn|Thomson|loc=Vol III, pp v – viii}}{{sfn|Thomson|loc=Vol IV, pp v – viii}}{{sfn|Thomson|loc=Vol V, pp vi – viii}}{{sfn|Thomson|loc=Vol VI, pp iii – vii}}{{sfn|Thomson|loc=Vol VII, pp iii – vii}}{{sfn|Thomson|loc=Vol VIII, pp iii – vii}}
