A '''priority certificate''' is a document attesting that the entities named in such a certificate are the first to discover a [[phenomenon]] from nature, the first proponent of a theory, abstract idea, solution to a problem, proof of a [[theorem]] etc. A person who makes a new and useful discovery is entitled to receive such a priority certificate for that specific discovery.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Comanescu |first=G. |last2=Hyndman |first2=K.G. |date=1 June 2015 |title=Priority certificates: a proposal for non-intrusive forms of IP |url=https://academic.oup.com/jiplp/article-abstract/10/6/429/919556 |journal=Journal of Intellectual Property Law & Practice |volume=10 |issue=6 |pages=429–447 |archive-date=2015 |access-date= }}</ref>
Private or public companies and organizations, such as universities, R&D institutions, trade shows and exhibitions are known to grant priority certificates to confer formal recognition upon the claimant(s).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.embedded-world.de/Filestore.aspx/Priority-Certificate-2017.pdf?fair=master&type=file&key=33cb35b1-3790-48a9-94b7-1fb163f9631a&language=en&filegroup=&filetype=file |title=The priority certificate |last=Heidrun |first=Lindner |publisher= |date=2013 |website=www.embedded-world.de |access-date=November 11, 2017}}</ref>
